answers.body_markdown:
You are locking the table, you should be doing a transaction.

    BEGIN ATOMIC
        SET OPERATION_NUMBER = (SELECT R08NRO + 1 FROM SMPORDD.R08FNTR where R08IDT = TYPE);
        UPDATE SMPORDD.R08FNTR SET R08NRO = OPERATION_NUMBER  WHERE R08IDT = TYPE; 
        COMMIT;
    END

As others have mentioned, using one or more sequence(s) will cause less lock contention. In addition, I&#39;m not 100% sure that your semaphore will work unless you use serializable isolation level (I think snapshot isolation level will also guarantee that, but it is not implemented in Db2).

If you don&#39;t mind gaps and that types get mixed from the same sequence, one sequence is the easiest possible scenario:

    SELECT R08NRO AS OPERATION_NUMBER
    FROM FINAL TABLE (
        UPDATE SMPORDD.R08FNTR 
            SET R08NRO = NEXT VAL FOR &lt;THE_SEQUENCE&gt;
        WHERE R08IDT = TYPE
    );

If needed, you can create one sequence per type and use dynamic sql to construct the name of the sequence (still wont prevent gaps though, a sequence number is consumed when it is pulled from the sequence, say in case of rollback)

What you are trying to do was a popular pattern in the beginning of the Java EE era. I get the impression that it was massively abandoned due to the problems it caused.

